title: Sainsmart Hall-Effect Rostock Z-Probe Automatic Bed Leveling

description.text:
This is a remix of the original but this one uses the Sainsmart Hall-Effect board.

you can find that here:
https://www.sainsmart.com/sainsmart-hall-effect-sensor-switch-magnetic-detector-module-for-arduino-motor.html

cheep and good...

for the rod I use a rod from a CD/DVD player / Rom, they seem to be all the same size.
The magnets are 3/16" cube.

You may need to ream out the hole as well as add a spring to make sure it comes back out...

some setup details

  1. make sure your magnets are orientated so they are in attraction.
  2. Bend the sensor down so its closer to the magnet on the rod. you want the sensor to trigger when the magnet gets close it.

  3. If its not triggering when it gets close but rather after it get past the sensor. Flip the magnets over. they need to be the correct orientation.

  4. Use the potentiometer ( that small things with a slot in it on the board) to adjust the sensitivity. This will adjust the triggering of the sensor.
    You want it to trigger with out the going to far where the rod goes up.

you can then set up your printer using G commands so that when it is done probing it goes down past the sensor height and then the rod will stay up.

if you get all the rod the right height this will be out of the way when printing. then when your ready to use it again just pull it out.

please leave a comment if you need more help.

~Russ

To make the boot a bit more realistic I added a bead of solder around the shifter to keep the boot down so it would flex like a real boot when shifting. You have to be quick with the solder because the shifter gets really hot and begins to melt the top of the boot. The way I figured out where to apply the bead is take the shifter out of the housing and pull the shift ball up into the boot and apply a couple small bumps on the shifter where you want the bead. Then take the shifter apart and finish so you wont melt the boot. Enjoy

description.text:
Modified Prusa MK2 extruder parts to fit 8, 12 and 18mm sensors, and the MK8 hobbed pulley.

12 July 2017: 12 and 18mm sensor mountings have been modified to provide more space for the sensor cable routing.

I have included the modified scad files, as required by the GPL license.
Note that these files may require additional files, which can be found in the Prusa GIT repository.

If you like my work, please consider a small donation.

Printer Brand:

Prusa

Printer:

Prusa Clone

Rafts:

No

Doesn't Matter

0.2

Infill:

25%

Notes:

Whilst waiting for my genuine Prusa i3 MK2 to arrive, and having been spurred on by Tom Sanladerer's Cheap i3 MK2 Clone videos, I went ahead and built my own 24V version of a Prusa i3 MK2 Clone using the STLs freely available on Prusa's GIT repository; a 6mm Aluminium frame; TR8x8 Z axis screws; a Hictop 3mm Aluminium heated bed; a 360W 24V PSU; and a genuine E3Dv6.

However, it became clear (and pointed out by Tom in a summary video) that the common MK8 extruder did not fit well onto the current design. I took to modifying the SCAD files to fix this issue, and a few others, and this is the result.

Modifications:

  1. Move hot-end 1mm right to accommodate the MK8 7mm effective diameter.
  2. Increase sensor fixing to hold the more common 12mm and 18mm sensors.
  3. Allow the sensor cable loop to fit without interference.

The 8mm sensor is approximately 21.5mm right and 9mm back from the nozzle.
The 12mm sensor is approximately 27mm right and 7mm back from the nozzle.
The 18mm sensor is approximately 32mm right and 3mm back from the nozzle.

Print in ABS 0.4mm nozzle; 0.2mm height; 2 shells; 3 layers top and bottom; 25% infill.

As I wanted a look-alike clone, I also modified the PSU cover to take a 24V 360W PSU, and the RAMBO cover to take a RAMPS 1.4/Arduino combo. These are posted seperately.
The last two pictures shows the completed clone and some sample printed parts. Running TMC2100 stepper drivers on the X and Y axes has made my machine almost silent!

license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
This thing allows you to use any - widely available - microphone iPad holder as a screen holder while flying the Mavic Pro.

Since I wanted to use my large iPad Pro to fly my Mavic Pro, I needed something stable and reliable.

I also wanted to have some support carrying the weight over a longer period of time, so I added something to attach a neck strap that I took from an old computer bag. In order to optimize the weight balance, I cut an old shoe string in half and used it in between the neck strap and the adapter.

The design consists of two parts: The Adapter (orange) that goes into the Mavic Pro Remote and a Bolt (silver) that fixes the iPad microphone holder against the Adapter. It is a standard 3/8 microphone diameter and has been generated with the help of the great Nut, Bolt, Washer and Threaded Rod Factory (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:193647) by mike_mattala.

I printed the Bolt in ABS with a solid infill at high quality. The Adapter was printed in PLA using 50% infill low quality. Both sliced by Cura 2.4. No special pre- or post- processing required.

When connecting the iPad to the Mavic remote, please make sure that you are using the USB connector (standard iPad USB cable) at the center of the remote and unplug the mini USB connecter on the left side of the remote.

Please always ensure that your printing quality is right before putting your expensive iPad on top of it. Use it at your own risk and feel the huge difference of a huge screen.

Enjoy,

title: Earphone Cable Clip
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
Made for people who use wired Earphones while out and about to keep their cables under control and out of harms way...

Whether you're listening to your music on your mobile device while commuting to/from work, out for a run or at the gym you really don't want your Earphone cable flying round, which is a nuisance, and is a safety risk because it may catch on things located nearby. This simple little clip is a great super low cost solution to keep yourself, your cable and your mobile device safe and the earphones in your ear (... and less likely to be pulled out as you move).

The clip is small so uses very little filament to print. It attaches onto any earphone cables (refer to images for fitting instructions) and once attached will not come off without reversing the process. The cable will however slide freely through the clip.

The clip works by being attached to the users clothing similar to attaching a (mini) peg that has a slot in one end for the cable to slide back and forth through. With the clip attached to the cable just clip it onto you shirt, shorts, jacket, jeans etc. to stop your cable from flying around which can be a nuisance and dangerous.

You can print these clips in next to no time and at minimal cost. Once installed on your cable they are just there for when you want them. They weigh only a few grams.

The clip has a surprising wide and strong bite for such a small print (Requires high infill). It will bite onto anything up to approx. 4mm wide and down to almost 0mm thickness.. However, when attaching a clip to very thin materials it is recommended to bunch the material slightly to ensure a good bite is achieved so the clip will stay secure.

This clip is super easy to print and use. If you ever use wired earphones with your mobile device while moving around this is worth having. Print some for yourself or great little things to give to friends, family or workmates. Improves safety, is practical and very handy....

As with any PLA 3D print the bite will weaken over time through use and it could break in the longer term. However, it's such a quick, small and low cost print just print another one or a batch.

The Earphone Cable Clip can also be used to clip your cable onto things to store them away when not in use.

Some mobile phone cables have a small clip, but not many, so if you are using wired earphones print and install one or two of these on your cable to keep it under control.

Please refer to the images and print instructions for additional information.... and post images of your Earphone Cable Clip in use for other members to see,

Note: If you like this check out the rest of my practical and fun designs.

title: Camera adapter for Kaiser System V enlarger, replaces RA-1

description.text:
Ever thought about using your old Kaiser System V enlarger as a camera stand for reproduction or macro photography? Not willing to spend ~100,-€ for the Kaiser RA-1 adapter? Make your own!

The adapter uses, besides the printed part, the following things:

  • Arca Swiss compatible camera mount, 50mm wide (mine is a MENGS CL-505)
  • M6x25 screw with washer and nut
  • the mounting bolt from the enlargers´ head and the nut (don´t try a different nut - it´s M10x1 - metric fine thread!)
  • some sheet metal, ~22x110x1.5mm (I used aluminum)

The bent metal part is used as washers inside the printed part, to cover the holes where the nuts are put in and, if the camera is heavy and the printed part breaks, the camera will not fall down ;-)

• The "fulljoint" is a 3-part assembly, with some rotational freedom in each arm and full rotational freedom (around one axis) in the center joint. With tolerances no greater than 0.1 in. and difficult gaps to reach, you may need a long, thin, and narrow blade to clean the print. A thin letter opener may be useful in that case. Always remember gloves and eye protection.

  • This is a multi-part construction, and the fulljoint requires a decent fill for stability: printing from ABS (with relatively hollow fills for all other parts), this used approximately 330 grams of filament.

  • Do not overtighten the bolts.

  • The clamps may be egg-shaped but should not be used to hold actual eggs.
    • This produces something similar to the "grabber toys" often sold by toy outlets, using a dual-arm construct that is operated like large scissors but clamps instead of cutting. It may have other uses, such as makeshift salad tongs or as a pooper-scooper for pets (whatever use you pick, pick one). For stability, the "arms" are kept short: I originally made extensions for the arms but they were too unstable. When printing, you need two postjoints, two handles, and 12 fasteners to make one complete object. The clampfasteners are indeed identical to the UTS #12 24UNC bolt (0.325in. length) that I submitted in a different file. Let me know if there are any unmentioned issues in the prints or construction. Give 'em the clamps!

• Print one fulljoint, and make sure the fulljoint has freedom to rotate, so that the full indent area in each arm is used between the two extreme positions (the arms rotate between 60 degrees and 90 degrees).

  • Print one firstclamp, one secondclamp, two postjoints, two handles, and 12 fasteners.

  • Insert the rectangular section of each handle into a similarly-sized hole in the fulljoint so the the handles curve away from each other like this (), not like )(. Use 4 fasteners with a flat-head screwdriver in fasten the handles in place, but do not overtighten the bolts.

  • Attach the postjoints to the fulljoint similarly: then should never touch, but the farthest extensions should be parallel when the fulljoint arms are at 60 degrees.

  • Attach the firstclamp to either postjoint, and the secondclamp to the other postjoint, so that the grooves mesh.

title: Anet A8 Swing Clamp down Brackets

description.text:
To quiet down my printer I needed it to mount it to a 2'x2' concrete paver, but I didn't want permanent clips. This clips swing over the threaded support rods and have a detent lock. It has lowered the sound by 8-12 Db (according to my phone app that I used). I no longer hear the printer outside of the room it is in. The paver is on 1/4" foam.

Place the clamps towards the middle of the threaded rods (I would recommend 4 clips) to allow slight deflection to get into the detent of the clip. The bracket will be centered at the edge of the rod. The holes allow for a M3x18 that just threads right in.

This is a hotshoe mount for a laser pointer. My use case is to mount a green laser to a camera to help point the camera for astrophotography, but you might find some other photography uses for it.

My laser pointer has a button that sticks out. The mount has an extra lip that you can rotate into position over the button, and keep the button pressed down (but be careful not to blind anyone with the laser, or to leave it on where an airplane might pass).

The mount is fully customizable so if your laser has different dimensions, or your hotshoe/printer has different tolerances, you can adjust it.

I used this to help with some simple photos I took at a darkish location. At 140mm zoom on a micro-4/3 camera, the precision of the mount and/or hotshoe was not enough to put the beam in the field of view. At more moderate zooms, the beam showed up nicely in the field of view--see the picture of the beam pointing to the Orion nebula.

The pictures were one minute exposures using an unmotorized barndoor mount. The green line is the laser. Note the faint meteor (I assume) track in the second--I didn't see it naked eye, but I was looking at the mount, nor the sky.

I had some focusing problems which you can see if you zoom in. On reflection, maybe the tip of the laser beam is far enough away to help with that, by letting one focus on it. I didn't think of that at the time--I just set the focus theoretically to the infinity range.

The duct tape on the tip of the laser helps hold in place an IR block filter I glued on the pointer, as my pointer was one of the cheap ebay ones that don't have an IR block filter (which makes them way more dangerous, as they emit more in IR than in green, and hence can damage eyes even more).

description.text:
Just a few things added to the very nice and simple design of MarkBenson.

  • The locking screw in the gear never realy worked for me. I though I could partly flatten the lead screw but then my gear broke so I decided to actually make a selflocking M8 nut variety . The gear now is sandwitched between to nuts and its quite stable.

  • I didnt want to use my drill for that purpose as I believe its a pain in the ass to constantly mount and dismount, so I went for the solution villamany opted. An old motor laying around salvaged from some garbage electronics, and a 3 dollar chuck from ebay would beat any price.

  • I also opted for a MDF base instead of the printed one. Its easier to make from some scrap piece, Its more sturdy and more heavy which adds stability to the whole drill press

Well print both parts or just the one if you opt for the one of it.  
the motor mount has to screw holes in the botom to secure the motor, 2 screws in the back to fasten to the main drill press and two screwholes in the side so as to provide for holding place for the retention spring.

comments.text:
I updated my post.
basically I needed a replacement gear for a stepper motor for work, in a big hurry.
I found a 16 tooth gear on the site and dropped it into Tinkercad in order to modify the diameter, height and added a center hole instead of the shaped hole that it already had. You can import an .STL file into Tinkercad and modify it easily.
I have searched extensively for the file that I used (GB_gears) so that I can give proper attribution to the creator, but I can't seem to find it again. It was for a set of gears and only one of them was a 16 tooth.
I am also looking for a better CAD program to learn. That being said, Tinkercad is a great starter (and a good learning tool to get your brain in the right thinking mode). You are restricted to using simple geometric shapes but it is amazing how much you can accomplish with a little thought. I have not even gone through all of the Tinkercad tutorials but am still pleased with the other things that I have created.
I really appreciate your comment.
I had actually posted it in order to show my boss. I never thought that I would get so many comments and downloads so quickly.
